TY  - JOUR
T1  - Undisclosed SEC Investigations
AU  - Blackburne, Terrence
AU  - Kepler, John D.
AU  - Quinn, Phillip J.
AU  - Taylor, Daniel
Y1  - 2020/10/29
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3805
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3805
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3403
EP  - 3418
VL  - 67
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - One of the hallmarks of the Security and Exchange Commision's (SEC's) investigative process is that it is shrouded in secrecy?only the SEC staff, high-level managers of the company being investigated, and outside counsel are typically aware of active investigations. We obtain novel data on all investigations closed by the SEC between 2000 and 2017?data that were heretofore nonpublic?and find that such investigations predict economically material declines in future firm performance. Despite evidence that the vast majority of these investigations are economically material, firms are not required to disclose them, and only 19% of investigations are initially disclosed. We examine whether corporate insiders exploit the undisclosed nature of these investigations for personal gain. Despite the undisclosed and economically material nature of these investigations, we find that insiders are not abstaining from trading. In particular, we find a pronounced spike in insider selling among undisclosed investigations with the most severe negative outcomes; and that abnormal selling activity appears highly opportunistic and earns significant abnormal returns. Our results suggest that SEC investigations are often undisclosed, economically material nonpublic events, and that insiders are trading in conjunction with these events. This paper was accepted by Suraj Srinivasan, accounting.
AB  - One of the hallmarks of the Security and Exchange Commision's (SEC's) investigative process is that it is shrouded in secrecy?only the SEC staff, high-level managers of the company being investigated, and outside counsel are typically aware of active investigations. We obtain novel data on all investigations closed by the SEC between 2000 and 2017?data that were heretofore nonpublic?and find that such investigations predict economically material declines in future firm performance. Despite evidence that the vast majority of these investigations are economically material, firms are not required to disclose them, and only 19% of investigations are initially disclosed. We examine whether corporate insiders exploit the undisclosed nature of these investigations for personal gain. Despite the undisclosed and economically material nature of these investigations, we find that insiders are not abstaining from trading. In particular, we find a pronounced spike in insider selling among undisclosed investigations with the most severe negative outcomes; and that abnormal selling activity appears highly opportunistic and earns significant abnormal returns. Our results suggest that SEC investigations are often undisclosed, economically material nonpublic events, and that insiders are trading in conjunction with these events. This paper was accepted by Suraj Srinivasan, accounting.
